1. Develop a web page with non-semantic elements <div> and <span>
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Non-Semantic Elements</title>
    <style>
        .container {
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            padding: 20px;
            border: 2px solid #ddd;
            text-align: center;
        }

        .header {
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            padding: 10px;
            font-size: 24px;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
        }

        .content {
            background-color: #28a745;
            color: white;
            padding: 20px;
            font-size: 18px;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
        }

        .highlight {
            color: #ff5733;
            font-weight: bold;
        }

        .note {
            color: #ffc107;
            font-style: italic;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <div class="container">
        <div class="header">
            Non-Semantic Elements Example
        </div>

        <div class="content">
            Welcome to this <span class="highlight">simple example</span> of using <span class="highlight">non-semantic elements</span> like <strong>&lt;div&gt;</strong> and <strong>&lt;span&gt;</strong> to structure a page.
        </div>

        <span class="note">Note: Although div and span are not semantically meaningful, they are useful for layout and styling.</span>
    </div>

</body>
</html>

2. Develop a web page with the semantic elements <form>, <table> and <article>
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Semantic Elements Example</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 20px;
            background-color: #f4f4f9;
        }

        form {
            background-color: #ffffff;
            padding: 20px;
            border-radius: 8px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
            margin-bottom: 40px;
        }

        form input, form select, form button {
            width: 100%;
            padding: 10px;
            margin: 10px 0;
            font-size: 16px;
        }

        form button {
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            cursor: pointer;
        }

        form button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }

        table {
            width: 100%;
            border-collapse: collapse;
            margin-bottom: 40px;
        }

        table, th, td {
            border: 1px solid #ddd;
        }

        th, td {
            padding: 12px;
            text-align: left;
        }

        th {
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
        }

        article {
            background-color: #ffffff;
            padding: 20px;
            border-radius: 8px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
        }

        article h2 {
            color: #333;
        }

        article p {
            font-size: 16px;
            color: #555;
        }

    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <article>
        <h2>Web Development Tips</h2>
        <p>In this article, we will explore some useful tips and tricks for web development using semantic HTML elements. Using semantic elements enhances the readability and accessibility of your webpages.</p>
    </article>

    <form action="/submit" method="POST">
        <h2>Registration Form</h2>
        <label for="name">Full Name:</label>
        <input type="text" id="name" name="name" required>

        <label for="email">Email Address:</label>
        <input type="email" id="email" name="email" required>

        <label for="gender">Gender:</label>
        <select id="gender" name="gender" required>
            <option value="male">Male</option>
            <option value="female">Female</option>
            <option value="other">Other</option>
        </select>

        <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    </form>

    <table>
        <caption>Employee List</caption>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>Name</th>
                <th>Position</th>
                <th>Department</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td>SATYA</td>
                <td>Software Engineer</td>
                <td>Engineering</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>ABHI</td>
                <td>Product Manager</td>
                <td>Product</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>RAMA</td>
                <td>UX Designer</td>
                <td>Design</td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>

</body>
</html>

3. Use all the HTML5 tags and develop a web page
article, aside, figcaption, figure,footer,header, hgroup,mark,nav, section,time
Good to
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>HTML5 Semantic Elements</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            background-color: #f9f9f9;
        }

        header, footer {
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            padding: 10px 20px;
            text-align: center;
        }

        nav {
            background-color: #333;
            padding: 10px 20px;
        }

        nav a {
            color: white;
            text-decoration: none;
            margin: 0 15px;
        }

        article {
            padding: 20px;
            margin: 20px;
            background-color: white;
            border-radius: 8px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
        }

        section {
            padding: 20px;
            margin: 20px;
            background-color: #e9ecef;
            border-radius: 8px;
        }

        aside {
            background-color: #f1f1f1;
            padding: 10px;
            margin: 20px 0;
            border-radius: 8px;
        }

        figure {
            text-align: center;
            margin: 20px;
        }

        figcaption {
            font-style: italic;
            color: #555;
        }

        mark {
            background-color: yellow;
        }

        time {
            font-size: 16px;
            color: #555;
        }

        footer {
            margin-top: 40px;
            background-color: #333;
            color: white;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <header>
        <h1>Welcome to Our Web Page</h1>
        <p>Discover content with HTML5 semantic elements</p>
    </header>

    <nav>
        <a href="#home">Home</a>
        <a href="#about">About</a>
        <a href="#services">Services</a>
        <a href="#contact">Contact</a>
    </nav>

    <main>
        <article>
            <h2>Understanding HTML5 Elements</h2>
            <p>HTML5 introduced many new semantic elements, providing more structure and meaning to a webpage. These elements are more descriptive and help search engines and other user agents understand the content better.</p>
            <section>
                <h3>What Are Semantic Elements?</h3>
                <p>Semantic elements describe their meaning in a human- and machine-readable way, making web pages more accessible and improving SEO.</p>
            </section>

            <time datetime="2025-03-08">March 8, 2025</time>

            <p>The <mark>HTML5 specification</mark> includes elements like <strong>article</strong>, <strong>section</strong>, and <strong>nav</strong> to structure content more effectively.</p>
        </article>

        <aside>
            <h3>Related Articles</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><a href="#">Semantic HTML Elements</a></li>
                <li><a href="#">The Evolution of Web Development</a></li>
                <li><a href="#">Best Practices in HTML5</a></li>
            </ul>
        </aside>

        <figure>
            <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/300" alt="Placeholder Image">
            <figcaption>This is an example of a figure with a caption.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <article>
            <h2>HTML5 and Modern Web Design</h2>
            <p>With the introduction of HTML5, web design has become more structured, providing designers with a powerful set of elements to create visually appealing and functional pages.</p>
        </article>
    </main>

    <footer>
        <p>&copy; 2025 Web Design Company</p>
        <p>Follow us on social media for more updates!</p>
    </footer>

</body>
</html>
